WEBVTT

00:25.520 --> 00:29.100
DRACULA by Bram Stoker

00:32.120 --> 00:33.320
Chapter 9

00:36.260 --> 00:36.860
Letter

00:37.500 --> 00:43.180
Mina Harker to Lucy Westenra, Budapest, 24 August

00:43.180 --> 00:51.280
My dearest Lucy, I know you will be anxious to hear all that has happened since we parted at the railway station at Whitby.

00:51.880 --> 00:57.980
Well, my dear, I got to Hull all right and caught the boat to Hamburg and then the train on here.

00:58.480 --> 01:09.280
I feel that I can hardly recall anything of the journey, except that I knew I was coming to Jonathan, and that as I should have to do some nursing, I had better get all the sleep I could.

01:10.260 --> 01:14.860
I found my dear one, oh so thin and pale and weak looking.

01:16.000 --> 01:22.880
All the resolution has gone out of his dear eyes, and that quiet dignity which I told you was in his face has vanished.

01:22.880 --> 01:30.180
He is only a wreck of himself, and he does not remember anything that has happened to him for a long time past.

01:30.980 --> 01:34.720
At least he wants me to believe so, and I shall never ask.

01:35.380 --> 01:42.600
He has had some terrible shock, and I fear it might tax his poor brain if he were to try to recall it.

01:43.560 --> 01:50.200
Sister Agatha, who is a good creature and a born nurse, tells me that he wanted her to tell me what they were.

01:50.200 --> 02:02.640
She would only cross herself and say she would never tell, that the ravings of the sick were the secrets of God, and that if a nurse through her vocation should hear them, she should respect her trust.

02:03.420 --> 02:12.520
She is a sweet, good soul, and the next day when she saw I was troubled, she opened up the subject my poor dear raved about, added,

02:12.520 --> 02:22.220
I can tell you this much my dear, that it was not about anything which he has done wrong himself, and you as his wife-to-be have no cause to be concerned.

02:22.860 --> 02:30.180
He has not forgotten you, or what he owes to you. His fear was of great and terrible things which no mortal can treat of.

02:30.840 --> 02:37.240
I do believe the dear soul thought I might be jealous lest my poor dear should have fallen in love with any other girl.

02:37.240 --> 02:48.120
The idea of my being jealous about Jonathan, and yet my dear let me whisper I felt a thrill of joy through me when I knew that no other woman was cause for trouble.

02:49.020 --> 02:54.900
I am now sitting by his bedside where I can see his face while he sleeps. He is waking.

02:56.260 --> 03:04.580
When he woke he asked me for his coat as he wanted to get me something from the pocket. I asked Sister Agatha and she brought all his things.

03:05.200 --> 03:12.980
I saw amongst them was his notebook. I was going to ask him to let me look at it, for I knew that I might find some clue to his trouble.

03:13.520 --> 03:21.280
But I suppose he must have seen my wish in my eyes, for he sent me over to the window, saying he wanted to be quite alone for a moment.

03:21.980 --> 03:26.640
Then he called me back and he said to me very solemnly, Wilhelmina.

03:28.100 --> 03:33.880
I knew then that he was in deadly earnest, for he has never called me by that name since he asked me to marry him.

03:34.480 --> 03:41.600
You know dear, my ideas of the trust between husband and wife, there should be no secret, no concealment.

03:42.160 --> 03:50.540
I have had a great shock and when I try to think of what it is I feel my head spin round and I do not know if it was real or the dreaming of the madman.

03:51.100 --> 03:57.580
You know I had brain fever and that is to be mad. The secret is here and I do not want to know it.

03:57.580 --> 04:06.820
I want to take up my life here, with our marriage. For, my dear, we had decided to be married as soon as the formalities are complete.

04:07.920 --> 04:26.200
Are you willing, Wilhelmina, to share my ignorance? Here is the book. Take it and keep it. Read it if you will, but never let me know unless, indeed, some solemn duty should come upon me to go back to the bitter hours, asleep or awake, sane or mad, recorded here.

04:27.040 --> 04:39.240
He fell back exhausted and I put the book under his pillow and kissed him. I have asked sister Agatha to beg the superior to let our wedding be this afternoon and am waiting her reply.

04:40.280 --> 04:50.360
She has come and told me that the chaplain of the English mission church has been sent for. We are to be married in an hour or as soon after as Jonathan awakes.

04:51.300 --> 04:57.660
Lucy, the time has come and gone. I feel very solemn but very, very happy.

04:58.400 --> 05:04.580
Jonathan woke a little after the hour and all was ready and he sat up in bed propped up with pillows.

05:05.380 --> 05:14.300
He answered his I will firmly and strong. I could hardly speak. My heart was so full that even those words seemed to choke me.

05:14.300 --> 05:25.540
The dear sisters were so kind. Please, God, I shall never, never forget them, nor the grave and sweet responsibilities I have taken upon me.

05:26.160 --> 05:32.680
I must tell you of my wedding present when the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband.

05:33.460 --> 05:40.380
Oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words my husband left me alone with my husband.

05:40.380 --> 05:49.080
I took the book from under his pillow and wrapped it up in white paper and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck

05:49.680 --> 05:55.620
and sealed it over the knot with sealing wax and for my seal I used my wedding ring.

05:56.380 --> 06:01.320
Then I kissed it and showed it to my husband and told him that I would keep it so

06:01.320 --> 06:07.080
and then it would be an outward and visible sign for us all our lives that we trusted each other

06:07.080 --> 06:13.040
that I would never open it unless it were for his own dear's sake or for the sake of some stern duty.

06:13.920 --> 06:20.120
Then he took my hand in his and, oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife's hand

06:20.760 --> 06:28.700
and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world and that he would go through all the past again to win it if need be.

06:28.700 --> 06:34.100
The poor dear meant to have set a part of the past but he cannot think of time yet

06:34.100 --> 06:39.160
and I shall not wonder if at first he mixes up not only the month but the year.

06:40.240 --> 06:47.100
Well, my dear, what could I say? I could only tell him that I was the happiest woman in all the wide world

06:47.100 --> 06:54.520
and that I had nothing to give him except myself, my life, and my trust

06:54.520 --> 06:58.680
and that with these went my love and duty for all the days of my life.

06:59.620 --> 07:07.000
And, my dear, when he kissed me and drew me to him with his poor weak hands, it was like a solemn pledge between us.

07:08.120 --> 07:14.620
Lucy, dear, do you know why I tell you all this? It is not only because it is all sweet to me

07:14.620 --> 07:17.860
but because you have been and are very dear to me.

07:17.860 --> 07:25.260
It was my privilege to be your friend and guide you when you came from the schoolroom to prepare for the world of life.

07:26.120 --> 07:31.200
I want you to see now, and with the eyes of a very happy wife, whether duty has led me

07:31.200 --> 07:35.640
so that in your own married life you too may be all happy as I am.

07:36.540 --> 07:41.600
My dear, please, Almighty God, your life, may it be all it promises.

07:41.600 --> 07:48.080
A long day of sunshine with no harsh wind, no forgetting duty, no distrust.

07:49.120 --> 07:55.940
I must not wish you no pain, for that can never be, but I do hope you will always be as happy as I am now.

07:56.560 --> 08:01.830
Good-bye, my dear. I shall post this at once and perhaps write you very soon again.

08:02.720 --> 08:07.100
I must stop, for Jonathan is waking. I must attend my husband.

08:07.640 --> 08:11.360
Your ever-loving, Mina Harker

08:11.360 --> 08:12.280
Letter

08:13.140 --> 08:15.920
Lucy Westenra to Mina Harker

08:15.920 --> 08:17.520
Whitby, 30 August

08:17.980 --> 08:23.700
My dearest Mina, oceans of love and millions of kisses, and may you soon be in your own home with your husband.

08:23.980 --> 08:26.740
I wish you were coming home soon enough to stay with us here.

08:27.000 --> 08:30.700
The strong air would soon restore Jonathan. It has quite restored me.

08:30.900 --> 08:35.360
I have an appetite like a cormorant. I am full of life and sleep well.

08:35.360 --> 08:41.440
You'll be glad to know that I have quite given up walking in my sleep. I think I have not stirred out of my bed for a week.

08:42.040 --> 08:44.000
That is when I once get into it at night.

08:44.880 --> 08:46.320
Arthur says I am getting fat.

08:46.860 --> 08:49.360
By the way, I forgot to tell you that Arthur is here.

08:49.720 --> 08:56.040
We have such walks and drives and rides and rowing and tennis and fishing together, and I love him more than ever.

08:56.440 --> 09:02.180
He tells me that he loves me more, but I doubt that, for at first he told me that he couldn't love me more than he did then.

09:02.680 --> 09:04.060
But this is nonsense.

09:04.060 --> 09:09.560
There he is calling to me, so no more just at present, from your loving Lucy.

09:10.600 --> 09:14.900
P.S. Mother sends her love. She seems better, poor dear.

09:15.880 --> 09:19.240
P.P.S. We are to be married on 28 September.

09:20.400 --> 09:22.060
Dr. Seward's Diary

09:23.040 --> 09:24.240
20 August

09:24.880 --> 09:28.260
The case of Renfield grows even more interesting.

09:29.340 --> 09:33.640
He is now so far quiet that there are spells of cessation from his passion.

09:33.640 --> 09:37.780
For the first week after his attack he was perpetually violent.

09:38.360 --> 09:43.220
Then one night, just as the moon rose, he grew quiet and kept murmuring to himself.

09:43.960 --> 09:46.220
Now I can wait. Now I can wait.

09:47.060 --> 09:50.960
The attendant came to tell me, so I ran down at once to have a look at him.

09:51.680 --> 09:54.900
He was still in the straight waistcoat and in the padded room,

09:55.240 --> 10:00.500
but the suffused look has gone from his face and his eyes had something of their old pleading.

10:01.300 --> 10:04.420
I might almost say cringing softness.

10:04.980 --> 10:08.880
I was satisfied with his present condition and directed him to be relieved.

10:09.580 --> 10:13.500
The attendants hesitated, but finally carried out my wishes without protest.

10:14.360 --> 10:18.160
It was a strange thing that the patient had humour enough to see their distrust,

10:18.240 --> 10:23.200
for, coming close to me, he said in a whisper, all the while looking furtively at them,

10:23.840 --> 10:27.560
they think I could hurt you, fancy me hurting you, the fools.

10:28.200 --> 10:32.880
It was soothing somehow to the feelings to find myself disassociated

10:32.880 --> 10:35.920
even in the mind of this poor madman from the others.

10:36.500 --> 10:38.860
But all the same I could not follow his thought.

10:39.620 --> 10:44.780
Am I to take it that I have anything in common with him, so that we are, as it were, to stand together?

10:45.800 --> 10:50.900
Or has he to gain from me some good so stupendous that my well-being is needful to him?

10:51.460 --> 10:53.320
I must find out later on.

10:54.080 --> 10:55.620
Tonight he will not speak.

10:56.120 --> 10:59.740
Even the offer of a kitten or even a full-grown cat will not tempt him.

11:00.220 --> 11:03.460
He will only say, I don't take any stock in cats.

11:04.020 --> 11:07.360
I have more to think of now, and I can wait, I can wait.

11:08.240 --> 11:09.920
After a while I left him.

11:10.220 --> 11:13.580
The attendant tells me that he was quiet until just before dawn,

11:14.040 --> 11:17.580
and that then he began to get uneasy, and at length violent,

11:17.580 --> 11:21.980
until at last he fell into a paroxysm which exhausted him,

11:22.000 --> 11:23.940
so that he swooned into a sort of coma.

11:24.860 --> 11:27.220
Three nights has the same thing happened.

11:27.580 --> 11:31.220
Violent all day, then quiet from moonrise to sunrise.

11:31.980 --> 11:34.300
I wish I could get some clue to the cause.

11:34.680 --> 11:38.380
It would almost seem as if there was some influence which came and went.

11:38.820 --> 11:39.600
Happy thought.

11:40.700 --> 11:44.220
We shall tonight play sane wits against mad ones.

11:44.880 --> 11:46.920
He escaped before without our help.

11:46.920 --> 11:49.040
Tonight he shall escape with it.

11:49.600 --> 11:53.840
We shall give him a chance and have the men ready to follow in case they are required.

11:55.700 --> 11:56.680
23rd August

11:57.520 --> 11:59.860
The expected always happens.

12:00.820 --> 12:03.300
How well does Rayleigh knew life.

12:04.240 --> 12:06.920
Our bird when he found the cage open would not fly,

12:07.160 --> 12:09.360
so all our subtle arrangements were for naught.

12:09.980 --> 12:11.980
At any rate we have proved one thing,

12:12.160 --> 12:15.080
that the spells of quietness last a reasonable time.

12:15.080 --> 12:19.980
We shall in future be able to ease his bonds for a few hours each day.

12:20.540 --> 12:24.240
I have given orders to the night attendant merely to shut him in the padded room

12:24.240 --> 12:27.620
and once he is quiet, until the hour before sunrise.

12:28.420 --> 12:33.400
The poor soul's body will enjoy the relief even if his mind cannot appreciate it.

12:33.880 --> 12:36.880
Hark! the unexpected again, I am called.

12:37.480 --> 12:39.340
Patient has once more escaped.

12:40.720 --> 12:41.240
Later.

12:42.260 --> 12:43.660
Another night adventure.

12:44.420 --> 12:48.260
Renfield artfully waited until the attendant was entering the room to inspect.

12:48.820 --> 12:51.520
Then he dashed out past him and flew down the passage.

12:52.100 --> 12:54.160
I sent word for the attendants to follow.

12:54.860 --> 12:57.300
Again he went into the grounds of the deserted house

12:57.300 --> 13:01.060
and we found him in the same place pressed against the old chapel door.

13:01.880 --> 13:03.800
When he saw me he became furious

13:03.800 --> 13:07.600
and had not the attendant seized him in time he would have tried to kill me.

13:07.940 --> 13:10.420
As we were holding him a strange thing happened.

13:10.820 --> 13:12.740
He suddenly redoubled his efforts

13:12.740 --> 13:15.120
and then as suddenly grew calm.

13:16.060 --> 13:18.640
I looked round instinctively but could see nothing.

13:19.420 --> 13:21.860
Then I caught the patient's eye and followed it

13:21.860 --> 13:25.040
but could trace nothing as it looked into the moonlight sky

13:25.040 --> 13:30.160
except a big bat which was flapping its silent and ghostly way to the west.

13:31.340 --> 13:35.180
Bats usually wheel about but this one seemed to go straight on

13:35.180 --> 13:39.000
as if it knew where it was bound for or had some intention of its own.

13:39.740 --> 13:43.580
The patient grew calmer every instant and presently said,

13:44.160 --> 13:46.620
You needn't tie me. I shall go quietly.

13:47.620 --> 13:49.640
Without trouble we came back to the house.

13:50.160 --> 13:54.160
I feel that there is something ominous in his calm and shall not forget this night.

13:56.260 --> 13:58.460
Lucy with Stenra's Diary.

13:58.660 --> 14:00.320
Hillingham 24 August.

14:00.800 --> 14:03.760
I must imitate Mina and keep writing things down.

14:04.060 --> 14:06.140
Then we can have long talks when we do meet.

14:06.580 --> 14:07.840
I wonder when it will be.

14:07.840 --> 14:10.800
I wish she were with me again for I feel so unhappy.

14:11.320 --> 14:14.820
Last night I seemed to be dreaming again just as I was at Whitby.

14:14.940 --> 14:17.620
Perhaps it is the change of air or getting home again.

14:17.900 --> 14:21.080
It is all dark and horrid to me for I can remember nothing

14:21.080 --> 14:26.320
but I am full of vague fear and I feel so weak and worn out.

14:26.760 --> 14:30.080
When Arthur came to lunch he looked quite grieved when he saw me

14:30.080 --> 14:32.220
and I had in the spirit to try to be cheerful.

14:32.640 --> 14:34.860
I wonder if I could sleep in mother's room tonight.

14:34.960 --> 14:36.940
I shall make an excuse to try.

14:39.600 --> 14:40.560
25 August.

14:41.140 --> 14:42.480
Another bad night.

14:43.240 --> 14:45.100
Mother Nut seemed to take to my proposal.

14:45.400 --> 14:48.740
She seems not too well herself and doubtless she fears to worry me.

14:49.120 --> 14:51.620
I tried to keep awake and succeeded for a while

14:51.620 --> 14:54.560
but when the clock struck twelve it waked me from a doze

14:54.560 --> 14:56.200
so I must have been falling asleep.

14:56.920 --> 14:59.540
There was a sort of scratching or flapping at the window

14:59.540 --> 15:02.700
but I did not mind it and as I remember no more

15:02.700 --> 15:04.460
I suppose I must have fallen asleep.

15:05.020 --> 15:06.120
More bad dreams.

15:06.120 --> 15:08.000
I wish I could remember them.

15:08.260 --> 15:10.100
This morning I am horribly weak.

15:10.380 --> 15:13.460
My face is ghastly pale and my throat pains me.

15:14.120 --> 15:15.940
It must be something wrong with my lungs

15:15.940 --> 15:17.840
for I don't seem to be getting air enough.

15:18.380 --> 15:20.400
I shall try to cheer up when Arthur comes

15:20.400 --> 15:23.040
or else I know he will be miserable to see me so.

15:26.180 --> 15:26.660
Letter.

15:27.740 --> 15:29.440
Arthur to Dr. Seward.

15:30.180 --> 15:31.220
Albemarle Hotel.

15:32.180 --> 15:33.220
31 August.

15:33.700 --> 15:36.820
My dear Jack, I want you to do me a favour.

15:37.600 --> 15:38.480
Lucy is ill.

15:38.840 --> 15:40.600
That is she has no special disease

15:40.600 --> 15:43.140
but she looks awful and is getting worse every day.

15:43.760 --> 15:45.560
I have asked her if there is any cause.

15:46.520 --> 15:48.200
I do not dare to ask her mother

15:48.200 --> 15:50.620
for to disturb the poor lady's mind about her daughter

15:50.620 --> 15:52.640
and her present state of health would be fatal.

15:53.660 --> 15:56.600
Mrs. Westenra has confided to me that her doom is spoken.

15:57.180 --> 15:58.200
Disease of the heart.

15:58.520 --> 16:00.180
The poor Lucy does not know it yet.

16:00.660 --> 16:02.800
I am sure that there is something praying

16:02.800 --> 16:04.200
on my dear girl's mind.

16:04.300 --> 16:06.660
I am almost distracted when I think of her.

16:07.280 --> 16:08.960
To look at her gives me a pang.

16:09.580 --> 16:11.400
I told her I should ask you to see her

16:11.400 --> 16:12.760
and though she demurred at first

16:12.760 --> 16:15.100
I know why, old fellow, she finally consented.

16:16.340 --> 16:19.140
It will be a painful task for you, I know, old friend,

16:19.240 --> 16:22.020
but it is for her sake and I must not hesitate to ask

16:22.020 --> 16:22.900
or you to act.

16:23.260 --> 16:25.300
You are to come at lunch at Hilling tomorrow.

16:26.340 --> 16:28.980
Two o'clock, so as not to arouse any suspicion

16:28.980 --> 16:30.040
of Mrs. Westenra.

16:30.500 --> 16:32.680
And after lunch Lucy will take an opportunity

16:32.680 --> 16:33.920
of being alone with you.

16:34.420 --> 16:36.900
I am filled with anxiety and I want to consult with you

16:36.900 --> 16:39.200
alone as soon as I can after you have seen her.

16:39.540 --> 16:40.600
Do not fail.

16:42.380 --> 16:42.900
Arthur

16:45.880 --> 16:46.400
TELEGRAM

16:46.960 --> 16:48.580
Arthur Holmwood to Seward

16:49.700 --> 16:50.740
1 September

16:50.740 --> 16:52.880
I am summoned to see my father,

16:52.940 --> 16:53.740
who is worse.

16:54.200 --> 16:56.980
I am writing. Write me fully by tonight's post

16:56.980 --> 16:57.520
to ring.

16:58.420 --> 16:59.920
Wire me if necessary.

17:02.100 --> 17:02.620
Letter

17:02.620 --> 17:05.080
from Dr. Seward to Arthur Holmwood

17:06.360 --> 17:07.400
2 September

17:08.300 --> 17:09.900
My dear old fellow,

17:10.420 --> 17:12.320
with regard to Mrs. Westenra's health

17:12.320 --> 17:13.980
I hasten to let you know at once

17:13.980 --> 17:16.800
that in my opinion there is not any functional disturbance

17:16.800 --> 17:18.760
or any malady that I know of.

17:19.080 --> 17:21.660
At the same time I am not by any means satisfied

17:21.660 --> 17:22.520
with her appearance.

17:22.920 --> 17:24.980
She is woefully different from what she was

17:24.980 --> 17:26.120
when I saw her last.

17:26.120 --> 17:28.100
Of course you must bear in mind

17:28.100 --> 17:30.380
that I have not had the full opportunity of examination

17:30.380 --> 17:31.500
such as I should wish.

17:32.040 --> 17:34.000
Our very friendship makes a little difficulty

17:34.000 --> 17:36.300
which not even medicinal science or custom

17:36.300 --> 17:37.140
can bridge over.

17:37.660 --> 17:39.620
I had better tell you exactly what happened,

17:39.700 --> 17:42.380
leaving you to draw, in a measure, your own conclusions.

17:42.780 --> 17:44.360
I shall then say what I have done

17:44.360 --> 17:45.320
and propose doing.

17:46.240 --> 17:48.940
I found Mrs. Westenra in seemingly gay spirits.

17:49.120 --> 17:50.200
Her mother was present

17:50.200 --> 17:51.980
and in a few seconds I made up my mind

17:51.980 --> 17:54.220
that she was trying all she knew to mislead her mother

17:54.220 --> 17:55.720
and prevent her from being anxious.

17:56.220 --> 17:58.560
I have no doubt she guesses if she does not know

17:58.560 --> 18:00.240
what need of caution there is.

18:01.040 --> 18:02.220
We lunched alone

18:02.220 --> 18:04.180
and as we all exerted ourselves to be

18:04.180 --> 18:06.280
cheerful we got, as some kind of reward

18:06.280 --> 18:08.360
for our labors, some real cheerfulness

18:08.360 --> 18:09.320
amongst us.

18:10.140 --> 18:12.160
Then Mrs. Westenra went to lie down

18:12.160 --> 18:13.620
and Lucy was left with me.

18:14.040 --> 18:15.300
We went into her boudoir.

18:16.080 --> 18:17.940
Until we got there her gaiety remained

18:17.940 --> 18:19.660
for the servants were coming and going.

18:20.400 --> 18:22.100
As soon as the door was closed however

18:22.100 --> 18:23.840
the mask fell from her face

18:23.840 --> 18:26.560
and she sunk down into a chair with a great sigh

18:26.560 --> 18:28.160
and hid her eyes with her hand.

18:28.700 --> 18:30.420
When I saw that her high spirits had

18:30.420 --> 18:32.180
failed I at once took advantage of her

18:32.180 --> 18:33.660
reaction to make a diagnosis.

18:34.480 --> 18:36.240
She said to me very sweetly,

18:36.420 --> 18:38.100
I cannot tell you how I loathe

18:38.100 --> 18:39.320
talking about myself.

18:39.860 --> 18:42.500
I reminded her that a doctor's confidence was sacred

18:42.500 --> 18:44.240
but that you were grievously anxious

18:44.240 --> 18:46.140
about her. She caught on

18:46.140 --> 18:48.280
to my meaning at once and settled that matter

18:48.280 --> 18:50.200
in a word. Tell author

18:50.200 --> 18:52.720
everything you choose. I do not care

18:52.720 --> 18:54.200
for myself but for him

18:54.200 --> 18:55.640
so I am quite free.

18:56.340 --> 18:58.300
I could easily see that she was somewhat

18:58.300 --> 19:00.200
bloodless but I could not see the usual

19:00.200 --> 19:02.680
anemic signs and by the chance

19:02.680 --> 19:04.520
I was able to test the actual quality

19:04.520 --> 19:06.360
of her blood. For an opening

19:06.360 --> 19:08.200
of the window which was stiff a cord

19:08.200 --> 19:10.400
gave way and she cut her hands

19:10.400 --> 19:11.900
slightly with broken glass.

19:12.380 --> 19:14.340
It was a slight matter in itself but it

19:14.340 --> 19:16.240
gave me an evident chance and I secured

19:16.240 --> 19:18.320
a few drops of the blood and have analyzed

19:18.320 --> 19:20.570
them. The qualitative analysis

19:21.060 --> 19:22.980
gave a quite normal condition

19:22.980 --> 19:24.620
and shows I should infer

19:24.620 --> 19:26.620
in itself a vigorous state of health.

19:27.220 --> 19:28.420
In other physical matters

19:28.420 --> 19:30.560
I was quite satisfied that there is no need

19:30.560 --> 19:32.520
for anxiety but as there must be

19:32.520 --> 19:34.560
a cause somewhere I have come to the conclusion

19:34.560 --> 19:36.160
that it must be something mental.

19:37.340 --> 19:38.740
She complains of difficulty

19:38.740 --> 19:40.900
breathing satisfactorily at times

19:40.900 --> 19:42.780
and of heavy lethargic

19:42.780 --> 19:44.700
sleep with dreams that frighten

19:44.700 --> 19:46.560
her but regarding which

19:46.560 --> 19:48.780
she can remember nothing. She says

19:48.780 --> 19:50.900
that as a child she used to walk in her sleep

19:50.900 --> 19:52.740
and that when in Whitby the habit came back

19:53.680 --> 19:54.760
and that once she

19:54.760 --> 19:56.760
walked out in the night and went out to Eastcliff

19:56.760 --> 19:58.620
where Miss Murray found her. But

19:58.620 --> 20:00.680
she assures me that of late that habit has not

20:00.680 --> 20:01.260
returned.

20:02.460 --> 20:04.540
I am in doubt and so have done the best

20:04.540 --> 20:06.600
thing I know of. I have written to

20:06.600 --> 20:08.540
my old friend and master, Professor

20:08.540 --> 20:10.520
Van Helsing of Amsterdam

20:10.520 --> 20:12.620
who knows as much about obscure diseases

20:12.620 --> 20:14.740
as anyone in the world. I have asked

20:14.740 --> 20:16.900
him to come over and as you told me that

20:16.900 --> 20:18.860
all things were to be at your charge I have mentioned

20:18.860 --> 20:20.700
to him who you are and your relation to

20:20.700 --> 20:22.880
Miss Westenra. This my dear

20:22.880 --> 20:24.840
fellow is an obedience to your wishes for I

20:24.840 --> 20:26.740
am only too proud and happy to do anything

20:26.740 --> 20:27.780
I can for her.

20:29.780 --> 20:31.100
Van Helsing would I know

20:31.100 --> 20:32.760
do anything for me for a personal

20:32.760 --> 20:34.760
reason so no matter on what ground he

20:34.760 --> 20:36.440
comes we must accept his wishes.

20:37.080 --> 20:39.080
He is a seemingly arbitrary man

20:39.080 --> 20:40.840
this is because he knows what he is talking

20:40.840 --> 20:42.360
about better than anyone else.

20:42.360 --> 20:44.360
He is a philosopher and a metaphysician

20:44.980 --> 20:46.660
and one of the most advanced scientists

20:46.660 --> 20:48.820
of its day and he has I believe

20:48.820 --> 20:50.380
an absolutely open mind.

20:50.780 --> 20:52.660
This with an iron nerve a temper

20:52.660 --> 20:54.760
of the ice brook and indomitable

20:54.760 --> 20:56.580
resolution, self command and

20:56.580 --> 20:58.680
toleration exalted from virtues to

20:58.680 --> 21:00.900
blessings and the kindliest

21:00.900 --> 21:02.500
and truest heart that beats.

21:03.320 --> 21:04.980
He is from his equipment for the noble

21:04.980 --> 21:06.760
work that he is doing for mankind

21:06.760 --> 21:09.040
work both in theory and practice

21:09.040 --> 21:10.700
for his views are as wide as his

21:10.700 --> 21:11.860
all embracing sympathy.

21:12.540 --> 21:14.560
I tell you these facts that you may know why

21:14.560 --> 21:16.080
I have such confidence in him.

21:16.480 --> 21:18.120
I have asked him to come at once.

21:18.500 --> 21:20.920
I shall see Miss Westenra tomorrow again.

21:21.280 --> 21:22.780
She is to meet me at the stores

21:22.780 --> 21:24.840
so that I may not alarm her mother by too early

21:24.840 --> 21:26.480
a repetition of my call.

21:27.820 --> 21:28.700
Yours always

21:28.700 --> 21:29.700
John Seward

21:32.100 --> 21:32.540
Letter

21:33.460 --> 21:34.700
Abraham Van Helsing

21:35.540 --> 21:37.480
M.D. D.P.H.

21:37.700 --> 21:38.840
D.L.I.T. etc.

21:39.420 --> 21:40.900
To Dr. Seward

21:41.940 --> 21:42.900
2. September

21:43.540 --> 21:44.900
My good friend,

21:45.040 --> 21:46.980
when I received your letter I am already

21:46.980 --> 21:49.020
coming to you. By good fortune I can

21:49.020 --> 21:50.940
leave just as once without wrong to

21:50.940 --> 21:52.500
any of those who have trusted me.

21:53.240 --> 21:54.920
Were fortune other, then it were bad

21:54.920 --> 21:56.980
for those who have trusted, for I come to my

21:56.980 --> 21:59.040
friend when he call me to aid those he holds

21:59.040 --> 22:00.860
dear. Tell your friend that

22:00.860 --> 22:03.000
when time you suck from my wound so swiftly

22:03.000 --> 22:05.080
the poison of the gangrene from that knife

22:05.080 --> 22:07.220
that our other friend too nervous let slip

22:07.220 --> 22:09.680
you did more for him when he wants my aids

22:09.680 --> 22:11.460
and you call for them than all his great

22:11.460 --> 22:13.600
fortune could do. But it is pleasure

22:13.600 --> 22:15.160
added to do for him, your friend,

22:15.200 --> 22:16.520
it is you that I come.

22:17.900 --> 22:19.360
Have near at hand and please

22:19.360 --> 22:21.380
it so arranged that we see the young lady

22:21.380 --> 22:23.560
not too late on tomorrow, for it is likely

22:23.560 --> 22:25.360
that I may have to return here that night.

22:25.780 --> 22:27.360
But if need be I shall come again

22:27.360 --> 22:29.600
in three days and stay longer if it must.

22:30.060 --> 22:31.640
Till then, good-bye,

22:31.860 --> 22:33.180
my friend John.

22:35.140 --> 22:36.020
Van Helsing

22:38.900 --> 22:39.380
Letters

22:39.380 --> 22:39.720
Letter

22:39.720 --> 22:42.020
Dr. Stuart to Hon. Arthur Holmwood

22:43.600 --> 22:44.560
3. September

22:45.240 --> 22:46.560
My dear Art,

22:46.940 --> 22:48.340
Van Helsing is come and gone.

22:48.480 --> 22:50.060
He came on with me to Hillingham and

22:50.060 --> 22:52.060
found that by Lucy's discretion her mother

22:52.060 --> 22:54.480
was lunching out so that we were alone with her.

22:55.380 --> 22:56.900
Van Helsing made a very careful

22:56.900 --> 22:58.280
examination of the patient.

22:58.440 --> 23:00.000
He is to report to me and I shall

23:00.000 --> 23:02.320
advise you, for of course I was not

23:02.320 --> 23:03.420
present all the time.

23:03.420 --> 23:05.700
He is, I fear, much concerned,

23:05.780 --> 23:07.640
but says he must think. When I told

23:07.640 --> 23:09.540
him of our friendship and how you trust me

23:09.540 --> 23:11.540
in the matter, he said, you must tell him

23:11.540 --> 23:13.700
all you think. Tell him, him,

23:13.700 --> 23:15.820
what I think, if you can guess it, if you will.

23:16.320 --> 23:17.600
Nay, I am not jesting.

23:17.640 --> 23:19.380
There is no jest, but life and death,

23:19.420 --> 23:20.200
perhaps more.

23:21.060 --> 23:23.340
I asked what he meant by that, for he was very

23:23.340 --> 23:25.380
serious. This was when we had come back

23:25.380 --> 23:27.280
to town and he was having a cup of tea

23:27.280 --> 23:29.520
before starting on his return to Amsterdam.

23:30.000 --> 23:31.480
He would not give me any further

23:31.480 --> 23:33.860
clue. You must not be angry with me,

23:34.060 --> 23:35.620
Art, because his very reticence

23:35.620 --> 23:37.720
means that all his brains are working for her

23:37.720 --> 23:39.720
good. He will speak plainly enough

23:39.720 --> 23:41.240
when the time comes, be sure.

23:41.720 --> 23:43.640
So I told him I would simply write an account

23:43.640 --> 23:45.580
of our visit, just as if I were doing

23:45.580 --> 23:47.680
a descriptive special article for the Daily

23:47.680 --> 23:49.660
Telegraph. He seemed not to

23:49.660 --> 23:51.620
notice, but remarked that the smuts of London

23:51.620 --> 23:53.500
were not quite so bad as they used to be when he

23:53.500 --> 23:55.580
was a student here. I am to

23:55.580 --> 23:57.480
get his report tomorrow if he can possibly

23:57.480 --> 23:59.520
make it. In any case, I am to have

23:59.520 --> 23:59.880
a letter.

24:01.080 --> 24:03.580
Well, as to the visit, Lucy

24:03.580 --> 24:05.520
was more cheerful than on the day I first

24:05.520 --> 24:07.260
saw her, and certainly looked better.

24:07.600 --> 24:09.400
She had lost something of the ghastly look

24:09.400 --> 24:11.580
that so upset you, and her breathing was normal.

24:11.920 --> 24:13.580
She was very sweet to the Professor,

24:13.800 --> 24:15.640
as she always is, and tried

24:15.640 --> 24:17.400
to make him feel at ease, though I could see

24:17.400 --> 24:19.800
the poor girl was making a hard struggle for it.

24:20.280 --> 24:21.640
I believe Van Helsing

24:21.640 --> 24:23.700
saw it too, for I saw the quick

24:23.700 --> 24:25.440
look under his bushy brows that I knew

24:25.440 --> 24:27.560
of old. Then he began to chat of

24:27.560 --> 24:29.700
all things except ourselves and diseases,

24:29.780 --> 24:31.880
and with such an infinite geniality

24:31.880 --> 24:33.740
that I could see poor Lucy's pretense

24:33.740 --> 24:35.640
of animation merge into reality.

24:36.140 --> 24:37.760
Then, without any seeming change,

24:37.780 --> 24:39.600
he brought the conversation gently round

24:39.600 --> 24:41.360
to his visit, and suavely said,

24:43.180 --> 24:45.700
My dear young Miss, I have the so

24:45.700 --> 24:47.440
great pleasure because you are so much

24:47.440 --> 24:49.640
beloved. That is much, my dear.

24:50.140 --> 24:51.960
Even there, that which I did not

24:51.960 --> 24:53.660
see. They told me you were down

24:53.660 --> 24:55.560
in the spirit, and that you were of a ghastly

24:55.560 --> 24:57.820
tale. To them I say poof,

24:58.140 --> 24:59.680
and he snapped his fingers at me

24:59.680 --> 25:01.700
and went on. But you and I shall

25:01.700 --> 25:03.560
show them how wrong they are. How

25:03.560 --> 25:05.620
can he, and he pointed at me with the same

25:05.620 --> 25:07.600
look and gesture as that which he pointed me

25:07.600 --> 25:09.780
out in his class, on and rather

25:09.780 --> 25:11.740
after a particular occasion which he never

25:11.740 --> 25:13.580
fails to remind me of, know

25:13.580 --> 25:15.140
anything of a young lady's.

25:15.460 --> 25:17.580
He had his mad men to play with and to bring

25:17.580 --> 25:19.620
them back to happiness, and to those

25:19.620 --> 25:21.520
that love them. It is much to do,

25:21.560 --> 25:23.660
and oh, but there are rewards in that we can bestow

25:23.660 --> 25:25.660
such happiness. But the young ladies,

25:26.000 --> 25:27.640
he has no wife nor daughter,

25:27.700 --> 25:29.580
and the young do not tell themselves to the young,

25:29.860 --> 25:31.780
but to the old, like me, who have known

25:31.780 --> 25:33.780
so many sorrows and the causes of them.

25:34.060 --> 25:35.800
So, my dear, we will send him away

25:35.800 --> 25:37.660
to smoke the cigarette in the garden, whilst

25:37.660 --> 25:40.000
you and I have a little talk all to ourselves.

25:40.660 --> 25:41.620
I took the hint

25:41.620 --> 25:43.780
and strolled about, and presently the professor

25:43.780 --> 25:45.720
came to the window and called me in.

25:46.060 --> 25:47.520
He looked grave, but said,

25:47.720 --> 25:49.640
I have made careful examination, but

25:49.640 --> 25:51.720
there is no functional cause. With

25:51.720 --> 25:53.980
you I agree that there has been much blood

25:53.980 --> 25:55.940
lost. It has been,

25:55.960 --> 25:57.920
but is not. But the conditions of her

25:57.920 --> 25:59.840
are in no way anemic. I have asked

25:59.840 --> 26:01.880
her to send me her maid, that I may ask just one

26:01.880 --> 26:03.960
or two questions, that so I may not chance

26:03.960 --> 26:05.760
to miss nothing. I know well

26:05.760 --> 26:08.140
what she will say, and yet there is cause.

26:08.540 --> 26:09.760
There is always cause for

26:09.760 --> 26:11.960
everything. I must go back home and think.

26:12.240 --> 26:13.880
You must send me the telegram every

26:13.880 --> 26:15.860
day, and if there is nothing because, I shall come

26:15.860 --> 26:17.860
again. The disease, for not to be

26:17.860 --> 26:19.760
well as the disease, interests me,

26:19.760 --> 26:22.000
and the sweet, young dear, she interests

26:22.000 --> 26:23.980
me too. She charmed me,

26:24.020 --> 26:24.760
and for her?

26:25.760 --> 26:27.980
It is not for you or disease, I come.

26:28.900 --> 26:29.800
As I tell you,

26:29.800 --> 26:31.820
he would not say a word more, even when we

26:31.820 --> 26:33.840
were alone, and so now, Art, you

26:33.840 --> 26:36.020
know all I know. I shall keep stern

26:36.020 --> 26:37.780
watch. I trust your poor

26:37.780 --> 26:39.940
father is rallying. It must be a

26:39.940 --> 26:41.940
terrible thing to you, my dear fellow, to be

26:41.940 --> 26:43.960
placed in such a position between two people

26:43.960 --> 26:45.340
who are both so dear to you.

26:45.700 --> 26:47.820
I know your idea of duty to your father, and

26:47.820 --> 26:50.080
you are right to stick to it. But if need be,

26:50.140 --> 26:52.160
I shall send you word to come at once to Lucy,

26:52.280 --> 26:53.920
so not be overanxious unless you

26:53.920 --> 26:55.240
hear from me.

26:57.420 --> 26:58.520
Dr. Seward's

26:58.960 --> 26:59.400
Diary

26:59.400 --> 27:01.020
4 September

27:02.020 --> 27:04.220
Zufiga's patient still keeps up our interest

27:04.220 --> 27:06.120
in him. He had only one outburst,

27:06.140 --> 27:07.820
and that was yesterday, at an unusual

27:07.820 --> 27:10.260
time. Just before the stroke of noon,

27:10.300 --> 27:11.560
he began to grow restless.

27:11.820 --> 27:13.840
The attendant knew the symptoms, and at once

27:13.840 --> 27:15.840
summoned aid. Fortunately,

27:15.840 --> 27:18.120
the men came at a run, and were just in time,

27:18.200 --> 27:20.060
for at the stroke of noon he became so

27:20.060 --> 27:21.960
violent that it took all their strength to hold

27:21.960 --> 27:24.140
him. In about five minutes, however,

27:24.180 --> 27:26.100
he began to get more quiet, and finally

27:26.100 --> 27:28.020
sank into a sort of melancholy, in

27:28.020 --> 27:29.900
which state he has remained up to now.

27:30.480 --> 27:32.200
The attendant tells me that his

27:32.200 --> 27:33.900
screams while in the paroxysm

27:33.900 --> 27:36.140
were really appalling. I found

27:36.140 --> 27:38.040
my hands full when I got in, attending

27:38.040 --> 27:39.920
to some of the other patients who were frightened

27:39.920 --> 27:42.240
by him. Indeed, I can quite understand

27:42.240 --> 27:44.020
the effect, for the sounds disturbed

27:44.020 --> 27:46.520
even me, though I was some distance away.

27:46.900 --> 27:48.380
It is now after the dinner hour

27:48.380 --> 27:50.260
of the asylum, and as yet my patient

27:50.260 --> 27:52.140
sits in a corner brooding with a

27:52.140 --> 27:54.000
dull, sullen, woe-begone look

27:54.000 --> 27:56.180
in his face, which seems rather to

27:56.180 --> 27:58.060
indicate than to show something directly.

27:58.400 --> 28:00.260
I cannot quite understand it.

28:01.540 --> 28:02.000
Later.

28:02.800 --> 28:04.280
Another change in my patient.

28:04.380 --> 28:06.100
At five o'clock I looked in on him

28:06.100 --> 28:08.360
and found him seemingly as happy and contented

28:08.360 --> 28:10.020
as he used to be. He was

28:10.020 --> 28:12.220
catching flies and eating them, and was keeping

28:12.220 --> 28:14.260
note of his capture by making nail marks

28:14.260 --> 28:16.340
on the edge of the door between the ridges of

28:16.340 --> 28:18.220
padding. When he saw me he

28:18.220 --> 28:20.280
came over and apologized for his bad

28:20.280 --> 28:22.160
conduct and asked me in a very humble,

28:22.400 --> 28:24.580
cringing way to be led back to his own room

28:24.580 --> 28:26.360
and to have his notebook again.

28:26.800 --> 28:28.260
I thought it well to humor him,

28:28.260 --> 28:30.480
so he is back in his room with the window open.

28:30.980 --> 28:32.460
He has the sugar of his tea

28:32.460 --> 28:34.240
spread out on the windowsill and is

28:34.240 --> 28:36.060
reaping quite a harvest of flies.

28:36.540 --> 28:38.140
He is not now eating them, but

28:38.140 --> 28:40.080
putting them into a box as of old,

28:40.080 --> 28:42.680
and is already examining the corners of his room

28:42.680 --> 28:43.640
to find a spider.

28:44.260 --> 28:46.120
I tried to get him to talk about the past

28:46.120 --> 28:48.220
few days, for any clue to his thoughts would be

28:48.220 --> 28:50.300
of an immense help to me, but he would not

28:50.300 --> 28:52.180
rise. For a moment or two

28:52.180 --> 28:54.200
he looked very sad and said in a sort

28:54.200 --> 28:56.180
of far away voice as though saying it

28:56.180 --> 28:57.840
rather to himself than to me.

28:58.560 --> 29:00.600
All over, all over,

29:00.820 --> 29:02.120
he has deserted me.

29:02.360 --> 29:04.260
No hope for me now unless I do it

29:04.260 --> 29:06.200
myself. Then suddenly

29:06.200 --> 29:08.200
turning to me in a resolute way he

29:08.200 --> 29:10.540
said, Doctor, won't you be

29:10.540 --> 29:12.240
very good to me and let me have a little

29:12.240 --> 29:14.280
more sugar? I think it would be very

29:14.280 --> 29:16.260
good for me. And the

29:16.260 --> 29:17.180
flies, I said.

29:18.380 --> 29:20.320
Yes, the flies like it too,

29:20.560 --> 29:22.320
and I like the flies, therefore

29:22.320 --> 29:24.220
I like it. And there are

29:24.220 --> 29:26.180
people who know so little as to think

29:26.180 --> 29:27.740
that madmen do not argue.

29:28.240 --> 29:30.180
I procured him a double supply and

29:30.180 --> 29:32.300
left him as happy as a man, I suppose,

29:32.520 --> 29:33.400
any in the world.

29:34.820 --> 29:36.300
I wish I could fathom his

29:36.300 --> 29:38.660
mind. Midnight,

29:39.200 --> 29:40.320
another change in him,

29:40.680 --> 29:41.840
I have been to see Miss

29:41.840 --> 29:43.840
Westernera whom I found much better

29:43.840 --> 29:46.060
and has just returned, and was standing

29:46.060 --> 29:48.140
at our own gate looking at the sunset

29:48.140 --> 29:49.820
when once more I heard him yelling.

29:50.320 --> 29:52.160
As his room is on the other side of the

29:52.160 --> 29:54.080
house I could bear it better in the morning.

29:54.660 --> 29:56.240
It was a shock to me to turn from

29:56.240 --> 29:58.160
the wonderful smoky beauty of a

29:58.160 --> 30:00.020
sunset over London with its lurid

30:00.020 --> 30:01.920
lights and inky shadows and all the

30:01.920 --> 30:03.800
marvellous tints that come on foul

30:03.800 --> 30:05.700
clouds, even as on foul water,

30:06.180 --> 30:07.760
and to realise all the grim

30:07.760 --> 30:09.700
sternness of my own cold stone

30:09.700 --> 30:11.760
building with its wealth of

30:11.760 --> 30:13.880
breathing misery and my own

30:13.880 --> 30:15.680
desolate heart to endure it all.

30:16.140 --> 30:17.880
I reached him just as the sun was

30:17.880 --> 30:19.800
going down and from his window saw

30:19.800 --> 30:21.220
the red disc sink.

30:21.820 --> 30:24.040
As it sank he became less and less

30:24.040 --> 30:25.760
frenzied and just as it dipped he

30:25.760 --> 30:27.360
slid from the hands that held him

30:27.360 --> 30:29.500
an inert mass on the floor.

30:30.420 --> 30:31.880
It is wonderful, however,

30:31.880 --> 30:33.820
with intellectual recubative power

30:33.820 --> 30:35.980
lunatics have for within a few

30:35.980 --> 30:37.740
minutes he stood up quite calmly and

30:37.740 --> 30:40.000
looked around him. I signalled to

30:40.000 --> 30:41.900
the attendants not to hold him for I was

30:41.900 --> 30:43.440
anxious to see what he would do.

30:43.860 --> 30:45.700
He went straight over to the window and

30:45.700 --> 30:47.160
brushed out the crumbs of sugar.

30:47.720 --> 30:49.640
Then he took his fly box and emptied it

30:49.640 --> 30:51.560
outside and threw away the box.

30:52.080 --> 30:53.760
Then he shut the window and crossing

30:53.760 --> 30:55.360
over sat down on his bed.

30:55.980 --> 30:58.160
All this surprised me so I asked him

30:58.160 --> 31:00.000
Are you going to keep

31:00.000 --> 31:01.040
flies anymore?

31:02.260 --> 31:03.740
No, said he.

31:03.980 --> 31:05.900
I am sick of all that rubbish.

31:06.780 --> 31:08.320
He certainly is a wonderfully

31:08.320 --> 31:09.420
interesting study.

31:09.960 --> 31:12.120
I wish I could get some glimpse of his mind

31:12.120 --> 31:13.940
or of the cause of his sudden passion.

31:14.640 --> 31:16.240
Stop. There may be a clue

31:16.240 --> 31:18.320
after all if we can find why today

31:18.320 --> 31:20.060
his paroxysms came on at

31:20.060 --> 31:21.440
high noon and at sunset.

31:22.320 --> 31:24.240
Can it be that there is a malign influence

31:24.240 --> 31:26.080
of the sun at periods which affect

31:26.080 --> 31:28.260
certain natures as at times

31:28.260 --> 31:29.420
the moon does others?

31:30.060 --> 31:32.060
We shall see.

31:59.440 --> 32:00.480
TELEGRAM SEWARD

32:00.480 --> 32:01.280
LONDON

32:01.280 --> 32:03.360
to Van Helsing, Amsterdam

32:03.360 --> 32:04.800
6 September

32:05.360 --> 32:06.980
Terrible change for the worse.

32:07.440 --> 32:09.460
Come at once. Do not lose an hour.

32:09.980 --> 32:12.360
I hold over Telegram to Holmwood till I've seen you.

32:29.260 --> 32:30.800
PISKED WEST

32:30.800 --> 32:32.160
PRINCE SEWARD ISLAND

